%[text] # Cold Plate Parameterization 
%[text] In this section, we will carry out a trade-off study to investigate different cold plate designs and compare a layout with U-channels (Figure 1) against a layout with parallel channels (Figure 2). This script is used to vary geometric parameters and compare performance of the two designs in terms of heat transfer and pressure drop.
%[text] The following schematic shows the relevant input parameters that will be used:
%[text] ![](text:image:492e)
%[text]  
%[text] ## **Geometric and Material Parameters of Cold Plate and Cold Plate Channels**
%[text] The U-shaped and parallel channel configurations will perform differently in terms heat dissipation and pressure drop depending on size of plate and channel geometry. We will perform a parametric sweep across geometric parameter variations and evaluate performance for both configurations by looking at the final device temperature, which is required to stay below a certain value, and the pressure drop across the cold plate. 
%[text] Packaging will constrain the size of the cold plate. Here we will vary the cold plate's length and width. These two parameters will also influence the overall channel length and surface area for convection available. For different channel areas we will only vary the channel width and leave the channel height constant. 
%[text] 
cpLength      = simscape.Value(180:30:330, "mm");    
cpWidth       = simscape.Value(180:30:330, "mm");    
cpThickness   = simscape.Value(5, "mm");   

channelWidth  = simscape.Value( 1:1:4, "mm");         
channelHeight = simscape.Value( 6, "mm");             
channelMargin = simscape.Value( 10, "mm");          
%%
%[text] ### Parameter Sweep for Cold Plate Configuration
%[text] To compare the two configurations, it is convenient to place them together in a single model. This will allow us to provide the same boundary conditions to both models at the same time.
open_system("example_compareColdPlates") %[output:529fa773]
%[text] 
%[text] ![](text:image:9b96)
%[text] For both configurations, [Pipe (TL)](https://www.mathworks.com/help/hydro/ref/pipetl.html) blocks are used to represent the abstract geometry of individual channels in the cold plate. Assuming the channels in the cold plate are identical to each other, we can use a single **Pipe (TL)** block along with custom blocks for dividing and combining flows to represent the entire cold plate. This is based on the assumption that the fluid and heat flows for each channel are identical. To achieve this, we created custom **Thermal Splitter** and **Flow Splitter** blocks, which can be used to divide and combine the flow (through) variables, i.e., heat, mass flow, and energy flow for a domain. 
%[text] To see how the assumptions above work, we can create a model with three identical networks of pipes. The first has three pipes in parallel and each loses heat to the environment. The second uses the Splitter blocks to achieve the same end. The second network requires only the equations for a single pipe, whereas the first one has a set of equations for each pipe. As the number of parallel channels increases, the model will be slower to compile and run even though it produces the same result.
open_system("example_FlowSplitter")
%[text] 
%[text] For both configurations, **Pipe (TL)** blocks are used to represent the geometry. Note that for the parallel channel configurations a **Flow Splitter** block is added on both sides of the pipe, and a **Thermal Splitter** is added at the **Pipe (TL)** thermal node. Assuming both the parallel channels and the parallel U-shaped passes have an equal geometry and the manifold is designed in such a way that the flow is evenly split between flow channels, we can only model one channel and one U-shaped pass, respectively. For such a case, the **Flow Splitter** acts as a multiplier and divider to make sure the flow in the thermal liquid domain is divided at the cold plate input and multiplied at the output. Similarly, the **Thermal Splitter** will divide the heat flow rate into the pipe. The multiplying and dividing factor will be the number of parallel channels. Both splitters are provided as a custom library:
open_system(projRoot + "\Libraries\supplemental_lib.slx")
%[text] For the parametric sweep a [Simulink.SimulationInput](https://www.mathworks.com/help/simulink/slref/simulink.simulationinput.html) object is used. In this model, the Model Workspace is already pre-populated with default parameters needed by the model (as defined in [ColdPlate](file:.\ColdPlate.m)), this avoids having to transfer base workspace variables to parallel workers when using parallel simulations in the next step. Additional parameters used include:
%[text:table]{"columnWidths":[407,492],"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Device diameter (mm) | 75 |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | Device surface area | pi\*("Device diameter"/2)^2 |
%[text] | Channel roughness ($\\mu${"editStyle":"visual"}m) | 15 |
%[text:table]
%[text] The following code creates the Simulink.SimulationInput object and uses the function [setVariable](https://www.mathworks.com/help/simulink/slref/simulink.simulationinput.setvariable.html) to set the swept and derived parameters for every simulation run. 
mdlName = "example_compareColdPlates";
clear simInp

% Pre-allocate SimulationInput
simInp(numel(cpLength),numel(cpWidth), numel(channelWidth)) = Simulink.SimulationInput(mdlName);

for i = 1:numel(cpLength)
    for j = 1:numel(cpWidth)
        for k = 1:numel(channelWidth)

            channelPitch = channelWidth(k) + simscape.Value(3, "mm");
            % U-shaped channels
            effFlowLengthU    = cpLength(i) - 2*channelMargin;                                    % Effective flow length of channels for U-shaped configuration
            numPassesU        = floor((cpWidth(j) - 2*channelMargin)/(2*channelPitch));           % Number of channel "U" passes based on the channel pitch for U-shaped configuration
            channelLengthU    = 2*effFlowLengthU;                                                 % Channel length for one U-shaped pass

            % Parallel channels
            channelLengthP    = cpWidth(j) - 2*channelMargin;                                     % Flow length of each parallel channel for parallel configuration
            numChannelsP      = floor((cpLength(i) - 2*channelMargin)/channelPitch);

            % Shared parameters
            channelArea       = channelHeight*channelWidth(k);                                    % Channel cross-sectional area
            channelDh         = 2*channelWidth(k)*channelHeight/(channelHeight+channelWidth(k));  % Channel hydraulic diameter

            % Calculating additional equivalent length to determine pressure drop
            % U-shaped channels
            numBendU          = 4;                                                                % Number of 90 degree bends in U-shaped configuration
            equivalentLengthU = numBendU*60*channelDh;                                            % Using an equivalent length to hydraulic diameter ratio of 60 for a 90° mitered elbow
            % Parallel channels
            numBendP          = 2;                                                                % Number of 90 degree bends in parallel channel configuration
            equivalentLengthP = numBendP*60*channelDh;                                            % Using an equivalent length to hydraulic diameter ratio of 60 for a 90° mitered elbow
            

            % Populating the Simulation.Input with variables, additionally a
            % PostSimFcn is set to calculate device temperature and cold
            % plate pressure drop for every run (see function at bottom of
            % this script)
            simInp(i,j,k)     = Simulink.SimulationInput(mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("cpLength", cpLength(i).value("mm"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("cpWidth", cpWidth(j).value("mm"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("channelWidth", channelWidth(k).value("mm"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("channelLengthU", channelLengthU.value("m"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("channelLengthP", channelLengthP.value("m"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("equivalentLengthU", equivalentLengthU.value("m"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("equivalentLengthP", equivalentLengthP.value("m"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("numPassesU", numPassesU, "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("numChannelsP", numChannelsP, "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setVariable("channelArea", channelArea.value("mm^2"), "Workspace",mdlName);
            simInp(i,j,k)     = simInp(i,j,k).setPostSimFcn(@(simOut)postSimFcn(simOut));
        end
    end
end

%%
%[text] #### Running the Parameter Sweep
%[text] The function [parsim](https://www.mathworks.com/help/simulink/slref/parsim.html) can help speed up the simulation by parallelizing the runs, if Parallel Computing Toolbox is not available, the simulations will be carried out in serial. The [Simulation Manager](https://www.mathworks.com/help/simulink/slref/simulationmanager.html) is visualized during the run, which allows for monitoring the simulations and visualizing the model output. For example, from the post-processing function:
simOut = parsim(simInp, UseFastRestart="on", ShowSimulationManager ="on" , ShowProgress="off");
%[text] ![](text:image:94c8)
%[text] Notice that for a given parameter set if the Simulation Manager gives an error or warning for one of the runs, you can investigate the error that was thrown by selecting the respective run in the *Simulations* tab and going to the *Diagnostics* tab.
%[text] We can use the Simulation manager to look at selected results during the run. Since we have defined a [postSimFcn](internal:M_9a9c), we can access some of the derived data we extract from the logged data and attached to the simulation logging:
%[text] ![](text:image:44c2)
%[text] 
%[text] 
%%
%[text] #### Visualize Results
%[text] In this section, we extract the final device temperature as well as the pressure drop across the geometry to compare both results and select a design. 
TDeviceU = reshape([simOut.TDeviceU],numel(cpLength), numel(cpWidth), numel(channelWidth));
TDeviceP = reshape([simOut.TDeviceP],numel(cpLength), numel(cpWidth), numel(channelWidth));
dpColdPlateU = reshape([simOut.dpColdPlateU],numel(cpLength), numel(cpWidth), numel(channelWidth));
dpColdPlateP = reshape([simOut.dpColdPlateP],numel(cpLength), numel(cpWidth), numel(channelWidth));


figure
tiledlayout(2,2)
nexttile
colormap hot
clim([25 80])

hold on
for k = 1:numel(channelWidth)
    surf(cpLength.value("m"),cpWidth.value("m"),TDeviceU(:,:,k), LineStyle = "none", FaceAlpha = 1/k)
    view([32 32])
    colorbar
end
title("U-Shaped Channels: Device Temperature")
xlabel("Cold plate length [m]")
ylabel("Cold plate width [m]")
zlabel("T [°C]")
hold off


nexttile
colormap hot
clim([25 80])

hold on
for k = 1:numel(channelWidth)
    surf(cpLength.value("m"),cpWidth.value("m"),TDeviceP(:,:,k), LineStyle = "none", FaceAlpha = 1/k)
    view([32 32])
    colorbar
end
title("Parallel Channels: Device Temperature")
xlabel("Cold plate length [m]")
ylabel("Cold plate width [m]")
zlabel("T [°C]")
hold off

nexttile
colormap parula

hold on
for k = 1:numel(channelWidth)
    surf(cpLength.value("m"),cpWidth.value("m"),dpColdPlateU(:,:,k), LineStyle = "none", FaceAlpha = 1/k)
    view([32 32])
    colorbar
end
title("U-Shaped Channels: Pressure Drop")
xlabel("Cold plate length [m]")
ylabel("Cold plate width [m]")
zlabel("\DeltaP [bar]")

hold off

nexttile
colormap parula

hold on
for k = 1:numel(channelWidth)
    surf(cpLength.value("m"),cpWidth.value("m"),dpColdPlateP(:,:,k), LineStyle = "none", FaceAlpha = 1/k)
    view([32 32])
    colorbar
end
title("Parallel Channels: Pressure Drop")
xlabel("Cold plate length [m]")
ylabel("Cold plate width [m]")
zlabel("\DeltaP [bar]")

hold off
%[text] We can see that the thermal performance is better in the U-shaped configuration, but it causes a higher pressure drop, due to the longer flow path for a single bend compared to one parallel channel. The parallel channels configuration typically has a better temperature uniformity. The pressure drop is quite low, we reach the smallest device temperature for a smaller channel width and larger cold plate length and width, resulting in more and longer channels and a larger surface area. 
%[text] Based on this, we could continue with an optimization. However, for the purpose of this tutorial, we will select a suitable solution from our current parameter sweep for which the final device parameter is a little below the maximum allowed temperature to give some safety margin. 
%[text] For the following steps, we select a design with the following parameters:
%[text:table]{"columnWidths":[407,492],"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Length cold plate (mm) | 240 |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | Width cold plate (mm) | 240 |
%[text] | Channel width (mm) | 1 |
%[text] | Channel height (mm) | 6 |
%[text:table]
%[text] and additionally
%[text:table]{"columnWidths":[407,492],"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Device diameter (mm) | 75 |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | Thickness cold plate (mm) | 5 |
%[text] | Channel roughness ($\\mu${"editStyle":"visual"}m) | 15 |
%[text] | Thermal conductivity of cold plate (W/(m\*K)) | 167 |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%%
%[text] #### Post-Simulation Function Used in Parameter Sweep to Calculate Additional Derived Outputs
function [newSimOut] = postSimFcn(simOut) %[text:anchor:M_9a9c]
    newSimOut = simOut;
    TDeviceTemp = simOut.simlog.Device_U_Shaped_Channels.T.series.values("degC");
    newSimOut.TDeviceU = TDeviceTemp(end);
    TDeviceTemp = simOut.simlog.Device_Parallel_Channels.T.series.values("degC");
    newSimOut.TDeviceP = TDeviceTemp(end);
    
    pATemp = simOut.simlog.U_Shaped_Channels.A.p.series.values("bar");
    pBTemp = simOut.simlog.U_Shaped_Channels.B.p.series.values("bar");
    newSimOut.dpColdPlateU = pATemp(end)-pBTemp(end);
    
    pATemp = simOut.simlog.Parallel_Channels.A.p.series.values("bar");
    pBTemp = simOut.simlog.Parallel_Channels.B.p.series.values("bar");
    newSimOut.dpColdPlateP = pATemp(end)-pBTemp(end);

end

